<div><span class = 'allcaps title'><b>TEMPLE HI LO</b></span></div><div>Embankments along the Los Angeles freeways are home to sprawling encampments of city dwellers.&nbsp; Miles of uncultivated land, barren in winters, and overgrown until serviced by the city in the spring and fall, these interstitial spaces provide outdoor refuge to people seeking temporary shelter.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><br><div>Tents and other provisional forms of temporary dwellings populate the spaces until they overcrowd and become so dense with debris and human bi-product that the city moves in to clear them in time for its annual summer fire season siting the reason as ’health hazard’ yet providing no real alternatives.&nbsp; For anyone who has lived in the city for some time, the emergence and clearance of these spaces, tent cities as some refer to them, are a routinized part of the Los Angeles landscape, the humans and their itinerant dwellings come and go like other items for clearance laid to waste in the so cal sun.</div><br><div>The highway that I lived off of for over fifteen years in Los Angeles was the 110 freeway.&nbsp; Built in 1952, it was quant by comparison to most others, with just three narrow lanes in the northern parts of its route, the route where I had a home.&nbsp; Often on my way downtown the traffic would be touch and go and I would sit idle alongside the freeway studying the tent life for signs of humans.&nbsp; There was one dwelling that caught my eye and always held my attention. I studied it the most closely.&nbsp; It marked the perimeter of its space using flags, torn fabric in a random pattern of yellow and white on wooden dowels staked in the ground.&nbsp; Some flags were larger than others but the space was organized following some kind of logic and it was a site that was active, actively changing and being cared for, it looked like a plan that someone was carrying out with intention, and I could never figure out if someone was living in the space or if it might serve some other purpose.</div><br><div>The day I rode the highway and discovered it was cleared with all the other temporary dwellings was shocking.&nbsp; It shouldn’t have been, the same thing would happen every year but who was ever ready for it, least of all its inhabitants.&nbsp; Like Sander’s hauntingly titled portfolio ‘The Last People’ — these were the city’s most vulnerable people — the mentally ill, the drug addicted, the abused, the damaged war veterans and victims of real state displacement and other untold traumas.&nbsp; The cops would swoop in and round up everyone, clearing humans with their mounting problems and belongings like brush under cover of the night.&nbsp; Whenever I drove past the space I would wonder what came of the person who’s project got demo’d, would they start over elsewhere, how would they begin living again now.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><br><div>Perhaps six months after this clearance I noticed that along a different freeway some flags went up near the crest of a hillside.&nbsp; One flag was quite large and pink, other flags marked a perimeter along with strands of glittery material that held a glint in the sun.&nbsp; It was more difficult to observe the scene from the car this time, highways at high speed are not ideal for deciphering messages in the landscape but after weeks of observation and mounting curiosity I drove to find it in the Elysian Fields across from Dodger Stadium.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><br><div>Finding the place was relatively easy as long as you knew what to look for.&nbsp; Small flags marked the way when I got to the top of the hill and parked the car along the road to be on foot.&nbsp; A small paved fire road served as a driveway of sorts and after walking in about 500 feet I was greeted by a temple alter with oranges and candles, some pieces of bread, and a man standing with a push cart with flags, red ones this time.&nbsp; He was friendly when I spoke with him.&nbsp; I asked if he was the same person that made the space off the 110 freeway and with a heavy Thai accent he told me that he was, that what I saw was the “Home Temple” and that this one here in the Elysian Fields was a “Ten Level Temple High and Low”.&nbsp; He said it was “ten-fold-left-and-right” with two white flags, two yellow, two black and two pink flags and that only once the flags are complete does he lay the foundation by taring everything up so he can see which way to set the plan.&nbsp; “The foundation for the Ten Level Temple was connected to every part of the land and to the world” he went on to say.&nbsp; It was hard to make sense of everything he was telling me and the freeway below was no help.&nbsp; He said we could talk again if I came back only I never had the luck of encountering him again even though I tried several times.&nbsp; He did warn me not to go into the temple though, he said it was dangerous because of humans and animals, and I reassured him that I would obey his wishes and not enter.&nbsp; I never did, to do so felt like a bad omen.</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps title'><b>STRAY</b></span></div><div>According to Wiki, asynchronous communication is the transmission of data that is not beholden to an external clock signal. Data on this path&nbsp;</div><div>travels intermittently instead of by steadily streaming which makes it possible to communicate at variable bit rates rather than at regular intervals.&nbsp;</div><div>In this form of telecommunication, transmitter and receiver clock generators are not exactly synchronized all of the time. Data can be sent one byte at a time with each byte preceded by a start bit and a stop bit.</div><br><div>Photography communicates mimetically using the apparatus of a camera or lens of some sort to copy the time that it sees reduplicating it and</div><div>stamping one time in-frame for another time out-of-frame.&nbsp;</div><br><div>Frames of images are frames of time, and frames of breath, suspended. Photography can also speak in the time frame of the index. One mark of exposure here, may be called by another an indexible mark there. The picture holds an interval of time as a mark-er of re-corded time.</div><br><div>But what about other forms of time such as asynchronous time or circular time, what about time that rotates or time that spins? Are there other types of time that pictures can hold?&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><br><div class = 'allcaps'>INDEFINITE TIME<br>INDETERMINATE TIME<br>DISPLACED TIME<br>ABSTRACT TIME<br>BILATERAL TIME<br>TRANSMISSION TIME<br>TRANSDUCED TIME</div><br><div>In 1987, Susan Howe published <span class = 'allcaps'>SINGULARITIES</span> which contains the poem <span class = 'allcaps'>ARTICULATION OF SOUND FORMS IN TIME</span> in bursts of verse and&nbsp;</div><div>found textual artifacts spread out over thirty-eight pages. On poetic time, Howe says this:</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps'>WHEN YOU WRITE A POEM YOU USE SOUNDS AND WORDS OUTSIDE TIME. YOU USE TIMELESS ARTICULATIONS.</span>&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>In 2002, Nathaniel Mackey published <span class = 'allcaps'>SPLAY ANTHEM</span> which includes the poem <span class = 'allcaps'>SONG OF THE ANDOUMBOULOU 50</span>, a serial poem that he began writing in 1985 and first published in the volume, <span class = 'allcaps'>ERODING WITNESS</span>. The poem has been published in units over the past few decades,&nbsp;</div><div>and is currently comprised of 250 units and counting. In Mackey’s essay <span class = 'allcaps'>SOUND AND SENTIMENT, SOUND AND SYMBOL</span>, he speaks of a kind of broken time:</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps'>POETIC LANGUAGE IS LANGUAGE OWNING UP TO BEING AN ORPHAN, TO ITS TENUOUS KINSHIP WITH THE THINGS IT OSTENSIBLY REFERS TO.</span>&nbsp;</div><br><div>I came across this piece of writing in the book <span class = 'allcaps'>THE POLITICS OF POETIC FORM: POETRY AND PUBLIC POLICY</span> where both Howe and Mackey’s writing co-exist albeit indirectly. For the next two years or so I focus my energies on bringing them together side-by-side privileging sight and sound over face with a name.</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps'><b>FRIENDS IN DEED</b></span></div><div>Since 1894, <span class = 'allcaps'>FRIENDS IN DEED</span> has been serving Pasadena, California’s homeless and at-risk communities. An interfaith organization, it works to meet basic human needs by providing supportive services so that homeless and at-risk neighbors can rebuild their lives.&nbsp;</div><br><div>A seal on the organizations website shows two brown hands, palms facing inwards and fingers pointed upwards to make space for receiving a green leaf falling from an imaginary sky above. The seal designates <span class = 'allcaps'>FRIENDS IN DEED</span> a ‘trauma informed organization.’&nbsp;</div><br><div>The Center for Disease Control identifies six guiding principals to a trauma informed approach:</div><br><div>1. Safety (house, home or shelter)</div><div>2. Trustworthiness &amp; Transparency (two hands clasping)</div><div>3. Peer Support (four interlocking hands)</div><div>4. Collaboration &amp; Mutuality (multiple bodies side-by-side)</div><div>5. Empowerment Voice &amp; Choice (an ear that is listening)</div><div>6. Cultural, historical, &amp; Gender Issues (shaking hands embedded in puzzle pieces)</div><br><div>An asterisk after the word DEED bares the additional message:&nbsp;</div><br><div>‘Doing together what we cannot do alone’</div><br><div>In Brent Hayes Edwards essay called “Notes on Poetics regarding Mackey’s “Song”, he talks about Mackey’s long-form poem as an embodied experience that makes “unstable progress down the page, its blanks and breaks, the creak of its reprises.”&nbsp; He goes on to reference the influence of the Dogon [peoples] cosmology on Mackey’s writing by quoting the French ethnologist Genevieve Calame-Griaule, whose “work on door-lock mecha­nisms in Dogon culture, has noted that:</div><br><div>In Dogon, as in some other African languages, the terms express­ ing the notions of 'to open' and 'to close' come from a single root whose first meaning is 'to close' Since it is the simple root that connotes the idea of 'to close,' and the derived form that of 'to open,' it seems legitimate to argue that the concept of closing precedes that of opening, and that one cannot, in Dogon logic, open a door until it has previously been closed. It seems that western logic proceeds more in the opposite sense, and considers that one closes that which is open, essentially in order to protect it.”</div><br><div>Edwards then concludes that “If Mackey’s Song creatively embraces the complexities of Dogon cosmology, then part of what the serial poem finds there is a sense that things close in order to open.”</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps'>FRIENDS IN DEED</span> gallery in San Francisco which was founded in 2019 by Micki Meng with Eric Li and Nazli Ercan.&nbsp;</div><br><div>The translation of the gallery’s Chinese name 想得開藝廊 is:&nbsp;</div><br><div>You can think open a problem to solve it.</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps'><b>GRACE WALKING AND TALKING</b></span></div><div>&nbsp;An excerpt from a letter on January 13, 2017:</div><br><div>I've been thinking quite a bit about Hope (Atherton) as a trans subject – not via gender, necessarily (though I'm of course drawn to the ambiguity of this "male" character having&nbsp; feminine name), but via the transgressing of borders that were established in colonial America, and were central to the colonial project. I'm thinking of Hope as a progenitor for all types of traitors – racial traitors, gender traitors, special traitors. And, to me, trans is always just a place-holder for a "crossing," not a crossing from one shore to another but perhaps an indefinite one, without arrival, without completion.&nbsp;</div><br><div>I’m sick of using the word trans – it's too loaded, too current in its signification – and "crossing," which is really the route of any transition, feels like a much more truthful representation of what it means to take the risk of leaving some norm behind, hoping towards an alternative.&nbsp;</div><br><div>- Cyrus Dunham</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps'><b>BOMBARDO</b></span></div><div>The poet Susan Howe references this made-up Native-American word in her book <span class = 'allcaps'>MY EMILY DICKINSON</span>, published in 1985. It originally stems from <span class = 'allcaps'>MAGNALIA CHRISTI AMERICANA</span>, an ecclesiastical book published in 1702 by the Puritan minister Cotton Mather. <span class = 'allcaps'>BREATHING, BOMBS, SWORDS, DEATH, SPEARS AND FLAMES</span>&nbsp;</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps'><b>WILL AND BE GOING TO</b></span></div><div>Within English grammar and verb tense usage the simple future tense has these two different forms of <span class = 'allcaps'>WILL</span> and <span class = 'allcaps'>BE GOING TO</span>. Although the two forms can sometimes be used interchangeably, they often express two very different meanings.&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><br><div>Loving Friends and Kindred:—&nbsp;</div><div>When I look back</div><div>So short on charity and good works</div><div>We are a small remnant</div><div>of <span class = 'allcaps'><b>SIGNAL ESCAPES</b></span> wonderful in themselves</div><div>We march from our camp a little</div><div>and come home</div><div>Lost the beaten track and so</div><div>River section dark all this time</div><div>We must not worry</div><div>how few we are and fall from each other</div><div>More than language can express</div><div>Hope for the artist in America &amp; etc</div><div>This is my birthday</div><div>These are the old home trees</div><br><div>Susan Howe, “Articulation of Sound Forms in Time,” from <span class = 'allcaps'>SINGULARITIES</span> (Wesleyan University Press), 1991.</div><br><div><span class = 'allcaps'><b>TREE ELLIPSES OR THE HOT WAR COUPLE</b></span></div><br>